I think that’s the same phenomenon viewed from another angle.

A novice holds a hammer.

A master no longer experiences “hammer” as a separate object.

The hammer becomes part of the body’s control loop.

Neuroscience gives this some grounding: people readily incorporate well-used tools into their sensorimotor system. Skilled tennis players, surgeons, and musicians often behave as if the racket, scalpel, or violin bow has become an extension of themselves rather than an external object.

The progression often looks like this:

Object
↓
Tool
↓
Interface
↓
Extension
↓
Embodiment

That’s a powerful developmental pattern.

Think about examples:

* A blind person’s cane becomes an extension of touch.
* A pianist doesn’t think about individual fingers—they think in phrases.
* A race car driver begins to “feel” the edges of the car.
* A programmer stops seeing syntax and starts seeing systems.
* A mathematician stops seeing symbols and starts seeing transformations.

The body schema expands.

